ystems (two-and-a-half degrees of freedom).This proof realizes a plan John Mather announced in 2003 but was unable to complete before his death. Kaloshin and Zhang follow Mather's strategy but emphasize a more Hamiltonian approach, tying together normal forms theory, hyperbolic theory, Mather theory, and weak KAM theory. Offering a complete, clean, and modern explanation of the steps involved in the proof, and a clear account of background material, this book is designed to be accessible to students as well as researchers. The result is a critical contribution to mathematical physics and dynamical systems, especially Hamiltonian systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aDiffusionxMathematical models. 0aHamiltonian systems. 7aSCIENCE / Mechanics / Dynamics.2bisacsh  aArnold’s paper.  aHamiltonian system.  aKAM theorem.  aaction variables.  aautonomous Hamiltonian system.  acelestial mechanics.  aconservation of action variables.  ainstability of dynamical systems.  aintegrable Hamiltonian systems.  alinearly stable.  amagnetic fields.  amotion of charged particles.  anegligible friction.  anon integrable.  aperturb.  aseveral degrees of freedom.  astable solution.1 aZhang, Ke, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Physics, Chemistry, Mat.Sc, Geosc 2020 Englishz978311070475408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Physics, Chemistry, Mat.Sc, Geosc 2020z9783110704556oZDB-23-DPC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Annals of Mathematics eBook-Package 1940